<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-180-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 180 290.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  March 23 1989 v37 n6 p133(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Master a second language for global international success.andO;(Recruitment) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baldwin, Harold.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Engineers who seek a competitive advantage for themselves andtheir companies in the increasingly international marketplaceshould consider mastering a second language.andP;  In addition totaking courses, renting a room to foreign colleagues or studentsand living or studying abroad should be pursued.andP;  Business peoplewho speak a second language, or several foreign languages, will beable to understand foreign colleagues and have better access tooverseas customers without having to deal with problems oftranslation.andP;  Knowledge of a foreign culture is as important tointernational business relationships as knowledge of the language.andO;Although German and Japanese are traditionally the most useful andsought-after second languages in technical fields, any languagemay prove helpful.andP;  Mastering a language will take time andeffort, but the payoff might be great.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Foreign LanguagesWorld MarketCompetitionEngineering EducationCareer Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>